{"parse":{"title":"Felicity conditions","pageid":22520384,"revid":788673198,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>In <a href=\"/wiki/J._L._Austin\" title=\"J. L. Austin\">J. L. Austin</a>'s formulation of <a href=\"/wiki/Speech_act\" title=\"Speech act\">speech act</a> theory, a <a href=\"/wiki/Performative_utterance\" title=\"Performative utterance\">performative utterance</a> is neither true nor false, but can instead be deemed \"felicitous\" or \"infelicitous\" according to a set of conditions whose interpretation differs depending on whether the <a href=\"/wiki/Utterance\" title=\"Utterance\">utterance</a> in question is a declaration (\"I sentence you to death\"), a request (\"I ask that you stop doing that\") or a warning (\"I warn you not to jump off the roof\").\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Felicity_conditions_for_declarations\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Felicity conditions for declarations</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Felicity_conditions_for_requests\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Felicity conditions for requests</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Felicity_conditions_for_warnings\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Felicity conditions for warnings</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Felicity_conditions_for_declarations\">Felicity conditions for declarations</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Felicity_conditions&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Felicity conditions for declarations\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><i>Conventionality of procedure</i>: the procedure (e.g. an <a href=\"/wiki/Oath\" title=\"Oath\">oath</a>) follows its conventional form</li>\n<li><i>Appropriate participants and circumstances</i>: the participants are able to perform a felicitous speech act under the circumstances (e.g. a judge can sentence a criminal in court, but not on the street)</li>\n<li><i>Complete execution</i>: the speaker completes the speech act without errors or interruptions</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Felicity_conditions_for_requests\">Felicity conditions for requests</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Felicity_conditions&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Felicity conditions for requests\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><i>Propositional content condition</i>: the requested act is a future act of the hearer</li>\n<li><i>Preparatory precondition</i>: 1) the speaker believes the hearer can perform the requested act; 2) it is not obvious that the hearer would perform the requested act without being asked</li>\n<li><i>Sincerity condition</i>: the speaker genuinely wants the hearer to perform the requested act</li>\n<li><i>Essential condition</i>: the utterance counts as an attempt by the speaker to have the hearer do an act</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Felicity_conditions_for_warnings\">Felicity conditions for warnings</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Felicity_conditions&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Felicity conditions for warnings\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><i>Propositional content condition</i>: it is a future event</li>\n<li><i>Preparatory precondition</i>: 1) the speaker believes the event will occur and be detrimental to the hearer; 2) the speaker believes that it is not obvious to the hearer that the event will occur</li>\n<li><i>Sincerity condition</i>: the speaker genuinely believes that the event will be detrimental to the hearer</li>\n<li><i>Essential condition</i>: the utterance counts as an attempt by the speaker to have the hearer recognize that a future event will be detrimental</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Felicity_conditions&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/John_Searle\" title=\"John Searle\">John Searle</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Illocutionary_act\" title=\"Illocutionary act\">Illocutionary act</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Pragmatics\" title=\"Pragmatics\">Pragmatics</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Felicity_conditions&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/J._L._Austin\" title=\"J. L. Austin\">Austin, J. L.</a> (1962) <i><a href=\"/wiki/How_to_Do_Things_With_Words\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"How to Do Things With Words\">How to Do Things With Words</a></i>. Oxford University Press.</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/John_Searle\" title=\"John Searle\">Searle, J. R.</a> (1969) <i>Speech acts</i>. Cambridge University Press.</li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2137\nCached time: 20180921222322\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.016 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.015 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 23/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 0/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 0/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 2/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 0/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%    0.000      1 -total\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:22520384-0!canonical and timestamp 20180921222322 and revision id 788673198\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","*":"Pragmatics"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Philosophy_of_language"}],"links":[{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"How to Do Things With Words"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Illocutionary act"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"J. L. Austin"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"John Searle"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Oath"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Performative utterance"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Pragmatics"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Speech act"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Utterance"}],"templates":[],"images":[],"externallinks":[],"sections":[{"toclevel":1,"level":"2","line":"Felicity conditions for declarations","number":"1","index":"1","fromtitle":"Felicity_conditions","byteoffset":432,"anchor":"Felicity_conditions_for_declarations"},{"toclevel":1,"level":"2","line":"Felicity conditions for requests","number":"2","index":"2","fromtitle":"Felicity_conditions","byteoffset":874,"anchor":"Felicity_conditions_for_requests"},{"toclevel":1,"level":"2","line":"Felicity conditions for warnings","number":"3","index":"3","fromtitle":"Felicity_conditions","byteoff